<subSubSection pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="118.[151,1436,685,961]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,829,853]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is now represented in collections by 
<specimenCount box="[878,998,829,853]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" type="male">five males</specimenCount>
. The elytral apices (
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[1223,1432,829,853]" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne, 1987a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,270,865,889]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1781,1804]" captionTargetBox="[176,1409,213,1735]" captionTargetId="figure-56@28.[164,1423,205,1741]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 6. Strict consensus tree for 61 IP analysis; consensus of 163 MPT of length 2615 from phylogenetic analysis of 61 Indo-Pacific study group taxa. New genera, new species, and still undescribed species in red, bold. Bremer supports above branches." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265352/files/figure.png" pageId="118" pageNumber="119">Fig. 6 e, f</figureCitation>
) are swollen and bulbous and thicker than the remainder of the epipleuron, so their interpretation as &quot;deflexed elytral apices&quot; differs slightly from others, where the deflexed apex of the elytron is anteriorly prolonged and no thicker than the rest of the elytron.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
